ce:section.ce:para:
To acquire insight into the fluorescence sensing mechanism of N,P@CDs@Eu toward TC in water, we carried out a series of examinations. Firstly, TC exhibited adsorption peaks within the UV–vis spectrum ranging from 250 to 450 nm and demonstrated significant overlap with the fluorescence excitation spectrum of N, P@CDs@Eu (Fig. 6
                        a). Hence, the fluorescence quenching at 440 nm of N,P@CDs@Eu could ascribe to fluorescence resonance energy transfer (FRET) or inner filter effect (IEF) [48]. In addition, the variation in fluorescence lifetime was examined to ascertain the cause of fluorescence quenching at 440 nm. The fluorescence lifetimes of N,P@CDs@Eu with and without TC was tested, which were fitted by a two-exponential decay function (Fig. 6b and Table 1
                        ). The fluorescence lifetimes of N,P@CDs@Eu and N,P@CDs@Eu + TC were identified to be 16.94 ns and 17.11 ns, respectively. The fluorescence lifetimes almost remained unchanged whether TC was present or not, confirming the quenching mechanism at 440 nm of N,P@CDs@Eu to be IEF [49].
